strategy: I tried to find a balance between how much of my time the events would take versus how likely I would find any joy there. If food is present, that's a plus. Alcohol doesn't matter since I'll have to drive home. I'd opt for a slightly longer drive time if it means less presentation time. I view these events as something I must do versus something I want to do, therefore I looked for the least time taken from me balanced with the pain of the gathering.
strategy2: The description of my strategy has not changed. I weighed the different factors based on how horrible they all were and chose the least painful.

strategy: I had a few important criteria's that I would look at, and the other ones didn't really affect my decision. First was the music, If it was up to me I would not go to any event where the music was bad, very bad, or moderate. So each event I looked at the music first, then the time was a small factor. If it was a 30 minute difference I would sacrifice some music quality to save travel time. Next was the amount of people, more people would be more fun. Those are the 3 main criteria's I looked at.
strategy2: I weighted each criteria differently, I went down my list starting with music, then distance, then people. If the music was completely opposite ( bad vs very good) I would 100% choose the very good. But if it was close, moderate and good I would look at the distance, and after the distance I would finally see the number of people attending the event.
metastrategy: After completing my choices, I learned about the different ways people make choices. I then chose the ones that best fit me. I chose multiple instead of one, I weighted them differently instead of all criteria's the same, and I also didnt choose a direct winner, If 2 options were close I went to my next criteria.

lex_comp1_description: Person description: When making his choices between events in Section 1, Ricardo only cared about the amount of food present; he always just chose whichever event had more food.

She cared about the duration the most, but also cared a little about the music and the socializing.
binwts_comp1_description: Person description: When making her choices between events in Section 2, Monica cared about four features: the duration of the event, the number of other people present, the quality of the music, and its distance from home. She cared the most about the duration and the number of other people present, but she also cared a little about the other two features.
binwts_comp2_description: Person description: When making her choices between events in Section 1, Leila cared about two features: the amount of food present and the amount of alcohol present. She cared about both of those two features an equal amount. To decide which event was better overall, she compared how much better each event was on those two features.
binatts_comp1_description: Person description: When making his choices between events in Section 1, Joe cared about three features: the distance from home, the amount of alcohol present, and the quality of the music. He considered the difference between the two events on each feature (e.g. 30 minutes away vs. 10 minutes away = a 20 minute difference in distance from home), and then weighed those differences together
binatts_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between events in Section 1, Xavier cared about three features: the quality of socializing, the amount of food present, and the number of other people present. He checked which event was better on each feature (i.e. which event 'won' on each feature), and chose the event that 'won' on a majority of the three features.
strategy: The first thing I looked at was the distance from home. If an event was very close to home, I looked at it first. Then I looked at quality of socializing - if I'm going to go out to an event, I want to socialize. But if the socializing was bad in both cases, the next thing I looked at was the food. If I'm going to go to an event with bad socializing, I should at least make it worth my while by eating some food. If distance, socializing and food were all pretty close to one another, I looked at quality of music and alcohol next. If one had better music or more alcohol, that's the one I chose. The things I rarely took into conisderation were the number of people at the event and the duration of the event. I'm usually the last one at a party and I can talk to anyone, so any scenario in that case worked for me.
strategy2: I thought I wasn't taking into consideration the number of people present and the duration of the event; however, after completing this section, I realized that I prefer more people at a party and that I prefer either a 60 minute or 90 minute party to something shorter. I chose 90 minutes over 80 minutes because it just seemed like a round number (an hour and a half) and somehow that appealed to me. I also realize that the amount of alcohol, which is not important to me really, can make a party more fun, in my opinion. So even though I don't drink a lot often, I like to be at a party where that option is there in case I'm feeling YOLO and want to party. It is also good for the other attendees of the party to have access to alcohol, as it can make everyone feel more social and keep things interesting.
metastrategy: I knew that distance was big for me, since I don't like using up a lot of time to get somewhere when I have good food and tv at home. I also knew that socializing was big for me, as that's something I don't have access to at home and isn't that the point of going out? I love eating and food was somewhat a factor. Like I said earlier, I can take or leave drinking and I can talk to anybody so those were factors that weren't huge for me.
meditation_exp6: I am relatively new to mindfulness meditation.

permission: Yes, I am okay with my answers to these questions
feedback: It was faster (I'm a fast reader). Some of the questions in Section 2 seemed obvious. Of course people are going to prefer a party with more food and better music! The study was fun, though.

She cared the most about the duration and the number of other people present, but she also cared a little about the other two features.
binatts_comp1_description: Person description: When making his choices between events in Section 1, Xavier cared about three features: the quality of socializing, the amount of food present, and the number of other people present. binatts_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between events in Section 1, Joe cared about three features: the distance from home, the amount of alcohol present, and the quality of the music. He considered the difference between the two events on each feature (e.g. 30 minutes away vs. 10 minutes away = a 20 minute difference in distance from home), and then weighed those differences together
strategy:
The drive time from home doesn't matter much to me. I'm fine driving to a party if it's going to be a good one and I'm going to see friends who I enjoy spending time with.
The length of the party is where my concern comes in. I have a limited social battery and generally find myself pretty exhausted by the time a long party is over. I'm the type of person who can only stay at a party for about two hours before I need to go home and recharge.
The amount of people at the party is also a small concern. I don't do very well in crowds, so the smaller and more intimate the group, the better.
When I go to a party, my needs are pretty basic. I wouldn't say that I'm a wallflower, but I can enjoy being included in social events and adding my own perspective where it is warranted. I'm comfortable with silence and I don't find it particularly awkward. The social aspect being low doesn't matter much to me as long as there are other distractions.
I like to eat, so having some good food is pretty nice. :)
I don't drink, so access to alcohol has no meaning to me.
The quality of the music doesn't matter much to me. I can assume that I will find some other place during the party to sit and relax without some crazy thumping in my ears.
Basically, you can think of me as a low maintenance person who likes to be with her friends when she has time. I don't have very many needs and I just like spending time with my friends. I like small parties with a few close friends, some decent food, a relaxing atmosphere and not too much time spent outside of the house.
strategy2: I think that the strategy that most fits my decision choice is strategy E. I do value certain aspects more than others equally and prefer that they all be present in some degree or another. It was very interesting to learn that my thought process could be summed up in a few different strategies. There were others that applied well, but I think this is the best match.
metastrategy:
I knew what my section 1 choice process was based on the options I was provided. I deliberated over each aspect of the party, decided on which features were most important to me and then chose based on the amount of these features present at the party. Generally speaking, I value:
a) Food available!
b) Duration.
c) Number of people present.

strategy: The most important thing was the quality of socializing. That is what I would value in the real world because if I felt awkward or uncomfortable at a social event I would leave. Food was completely unimportant. I did not care much about the other factors but I think that I preferred smaller crowd sizes on average.
strategy2: I almost completely focused on the quality of socializing. Then I focused a little on the amount of people attending.
metastrategy: I knew that I cared most about the quality of socializing but not completely (I gave about 99% importance to this factor).
